# SOLID Principles

- Single responsibility: controllers handle HTTP, use cases coordinate business actions, repositories persist data.
- Open/closed: extend behavior through new handlers, services, or repository implementations instead of large conditional branches.
- Liskov substitution: implementations of a contract must preserve expected behavior, errors, and return types.
- Interface segregation: prefer small repository or service contracts shaped around actual consumers.
- Dependency inversion: high-level business logic depends on abstractions, while `infrastructure` provides concrete implementations.
- In this codebase, prefer composition and dependency injection over inheritance-heavy designs.
